data.body:
In our Windows/DirectX application the lowest resolution mipmap levels of DXT textures are black. 

There is following code in Texture2D: 

```
// For DXT textures the width and height of each level is a multiple of 4.
                        // The last two mip levels require the width and height to be passed as 2x2 and 1x1, but
                        // there needs to be enough data passed to occupy a 4x4 block.
                        // Ref: http://www.mentby.com/Group/mac-opengl/issue-with-dxt-mipmapped-textures.html 
                        if (_format == SurfaceFormat.Dxt1 ||
                            _format == SurfaceFormat.Dxt1a ||
                            _format == SurfaceFormat.Dxt3 ||
                            _format == SurfaceFormat.Dxt5)
                        {
                            if (w > 4)
                                w = (w + 3) & ~3;
                            if (h > 4)
                                h = (h + 3) & ~3;
                        }
```

(https://github.com/mono/MonoGame/blob/450733b035add1a359033a0aefdc5dc2ea6fa2af/MonoGame.Framework/Graphics/Texture2D.cs#L327-L340)

Without `if (w > 4)` and `if (h > 4)` the textures are displayed correctly (in DirectX). 
I believe those if statements were added in following commit by @KonajuGames: https://github.com/mono/MonoGame/commit/620642b6c470a54a56f7d6700103dce243160bb6. 
It seems the ifs are needed for OpenGL, but not for DirectX.

Was this change tested with DirectX or only with OpenGL?

P.S. I guess TextureCube has the same problem.

hey all,

so i've been battling issues with rendertargets in iOS (https://github.com/mono/MonoGame/issues/1641), and i'm stuck and unable to push an update for my game. i finally tried refactoring my game to draw shapes without rendertargets. unfortunately, after the refactor, i have run into a new issue (or the source of the other). i am trying to use a BasicEffect with a texture to draw my shapes.

it looks fine in XNA Windows, but it draws solid white shapes in iOS. it looks like the call to GraphicsDevice.DrawUserPrimitives() is drawing the correct shapes, but the texture is not being applied, it's just drawing white.

initally i set up the effect like so.

``` C#
_WallEffect.World = Matrix.Identity;
_WallEffect.View = Matrix.CreateLookAt(new Vector3(0, 0, 1), Vector3.Zero, Vector3.Up) * _Camera.SimView;
_WallEffect.Projection = _Camera.SimProjection;
_WallEffect.TextureEnabled = true;
_WallEffect.Texture = _WallTexture;
_WallEffect.VertexColorEnabled = true;
```

then later i do some drawing:

``` C#
_Effect.Techniques[0].Passes[0].Apply();

graphicsDevice.DrawUserPrimitives(PrimitiveType.TriangleList, verticesFill, 0, verticesFill.Length / 3);
```

any help is appreciated, i'm stuck

Using XNA, I was able to create a new GraphicsDeviceManager(myGame) and use the attached GraphicsDevice during the construction of myGame by first calling ApplyChanges():

``` c#
class MyGame : Game
{
    public MyGame()
    {
        var graphicsDeviceManager = new GraphicsDeviceManager(this);

        // Do some configuration...
        graphicsDeviceManager.ApplyChanges();

        System.Diagnostics.Debug.Assert(graphicsDeviceManager.GraphicsDevice != null);
    }
}
```

In MonoGame Windows, this assertion fails.
